{"title_page": "Robert Bourne (developer)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Robert Bourne}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=January 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n{{tone|date=January 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n'''Robert Bourne''' (born 16 May 1951) is a British [[property developer]], [[entrepreneur]] and [[philanthropist]] who was born in [[London]], UK. Bourne has amassed a vast property and leisure empire in London and France and has achieved wide recognition for his patronage of the dramatic arts with his wife, theatre impresario, Sally Greene OBE.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/richlist/person/0,,38684,00.html | work=The Times | first=Charles | last=Bremner|title = Sunday Times Rich List 2005}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nBourne established an International Division which includes two hotels in France, in Courchevel and St Tropez. However, in a move widely condemned locally, Bourne purchased and immediately gave notice of closing within a month the little zoo of St Jean Cap Ferrat, with animals to be dispersed elsewhere and replaced by a luxury spa. He later agreed to sell the land and zoo at the price he paid, i.e. around 20 million Euros, to any public body interested in buying.<ref>''Nice Matin'', 15 October 2009</ref>]\n\nHe is a former Labour Party donor.<ref>https://www.google.com/search?q=Robert+Bourne+labour&rlz=1C1GCEB_enGB857GB857&oq=Robert+Bourne+labour&aqs=chrome..69i57j33.1716j0j4&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8</ref>\n\n== Millennium Dome ==\nIn 2001 Robert Bourne led a consortium of high-profile investors in a bid to buy the Millennium Dome from the Government. The Legacy consortium bid \u00a3125m for the Dome, planning to turn it into a high-tech \u201cKnowledge City\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/1107689.stm|title=Dome bidder foresees fast profit|date=9 January 2001|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropic activity ==\n'''The Old Vic'''<br />\nIn 1998 The [[Old Vic]] was in decline and faced threats of becoming a [[Lap dance|lap dancing]] club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/125531.stm|title=Old Vic theatre saved |date=3 July 1998|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 June 2008}}</ref> After public outcry and a plea from the Culture Secretary, [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]] for a patron to step forward and purchase the theatre. Robert Bourne and Sally Greene set up The Old Vic Theatre Trust, acquired the theatre. In 2003 Bourne and his wife persuaded Oscar-winning American actor [[Kevin Spacey]] to take on the role as artistic director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2004/04/26/btspace24.xml|title='The Old Vic building itself seemed to speak to me'|date=26 April 2004|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=9 June 2008 | first=Charles | last=Spencer}}</ref> \n\n== RADA ==\nBourne is an Associate Member of RADA ([[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]).{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourne, Robert}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Robert Bourne}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=January 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n{{tone|date=January 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n'''Robert Bourne''' (born 16 May 1951) is a British [[property developer]], [[entrepreneur]] and [[philanthropist]] who was born in [[London]], UK. Bourne has amassed a vast property and leisure empire in London and France and has achieved wide recognition for his patronage of the dramatic arts with his wife, theatre impresario, Sally Greene OBE.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/richlist/person/0,,38684,00.html | work=The Times | first=Charles | last=Bremner|title = Sunday Times Rich List 2005}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nBourne established an International Division which includes two hotels in France, in Courchevel and St Tropez. However, in a move widely condemned locally, Bourne purchased and immediately gave notice of closing within a month the little zoo of St Jean Cap Ferrat, with animals to be dispersed elsewhere and replaced by a luxury spa. He later agreed to sell the land and zoo at the price he paid, i.e. around 20 million Euros, to any public body interested in buying.<ref>''Nice Matin'', 15 October 2009</ref>\n\n== Millennium Dome ==\nIn 2001 Robert Bourne led a consortium of high-profile investors in a bid to buy the Millennium Dome from the Government. The Legacy consortium bid \u00a3125m for the Dome, planning to turn it into a high-tech \u201cKnowledge City\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/1107689.stm|title=Dome bidder foresees fast profit|date=9 January 2001|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropic activity ==\n'''The Old Vic'''<br />\nIn 1998 The [[Old Vic]] was in decline and faced threats of becoming a [[Lap dance|lap dancing]] club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/125531.stm|title=Old Vic theatre saved |date=3 July 1998|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 June 2008}}</ref> After public outcry and a plea from the Culture Secretary, [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]] for a patron to step forward and purchase the theatre. Robert Bourne and Sally Greene set up The Old Vic Theatre Trust, acquired the theatre. In 2003 Bourne and his wife persuaded Oscar-winning American actor [[Kevin Spacey]] to take on the role as artistic director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2004/04/26/btspace24.xml|title='The Old Vic building itself seemed to speak to me'|date=26 April 2004|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=9 June 2008 | first=Charles | last=Spencer}}</ref> \n\n== RADA ==\nBourne is an Associate Member of RADA ([[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]).{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourne, Robert}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n", "name_user": "HonkyDory64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Bourne_(developer)"}
